CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md
CONTRIBUTING.md
     3â†’# Contributing
     4â†’
     5â†’## Code of Conduct
     6â†’
     7â†’All interactions in the **npm** organization on GitHub are considered to be covered by our standard [Code of Conduct](https://docs.npmjs.com/policies/conduct).
     8â†’
     9â†’## Reporting Bugs
    10â†’
    11â†’Before submitting a new bug report please search for an existing or similar report.
    12â†’
    13â†’Use one of our existing issue templates if you believe you've come across a unique problem.
    14â†’
    15â†’Duplicate issues, or issues that don't use one of our templates may get closed without a response.
    16â†’
    17â†’## Pull Request Conventions
    18â†’
    19â†’### Commits
    20â†’
    21â†’We use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/).
    22â†’
    23â†’When opening a pull request please be sure that either the pull request title, or each commit in the pull request, has one of the following prefixes:
    24â†’
    25â†’ - `feat`: For when introducing a new feature.  The result will be a new semver minor version of the package when it is next published.
    26â†’ - `fix`: For bug fixes. The result will be a new semver patch version of the package when it is next published.
    27â†’ - `docs`: For documentation updates.  The result will be a new semver patch version of the package when it is next published.
    28â†’ - `chore`: For changes that do not affect the published module.  Often these are changes to tests.  The result will be *no* change to the version of the package when it is next published (as the commit does not affect the published version).
    29â†’
    30â†’### Test Coverage
    31â†’
    32â†’Pull requests made against this repo will run `npm test` automatically.  Please make sure tests pass locally before submitting a PR.
    33â†’
    34â†’Every new feature or bug fix should come with a corresponding test or tests that validate the solutions. Testing also reports on code coverage and will fail if code coverage drops.
    35â†’
    36â†’### Linting
    37â†’
    38â†’Linting is also done automatically once tests pass.  `npm run lintfix` will fix most linting errors automatically.
    39â†’
    40â†’Please make sure linting passes before submitting a PR.
    41â†’
    42â†’## What _not_ to contribute?
    43â†’
    44â†’### Dependencies
    45â†’
    46â†’It should be noted that our team does not accept third-party dependency updates/PRs.  If you submit a PR trying to update our dependencies we will close it with or without a reference to these contribution guidelines.
    47â†’
    48â†’### Tools/Automation
    49â†’
    50â†’Our core team is responsible for the maintenance of the tooling/automation in this project and we ask contributors to not make changes to these when contributing (e.g. `.github/*`, `.eslintrc.json`, `.licensee.json`).  Most of those files also have a header at the top to remind folks they are automatically generated.  Pull requests that alter these will not be accepted.
README.md
     4â†’## Note
     5â†’
     6â†’-   Sections are treated as nested objects.
     7â†’
     8â†’-   Section-less items are treated as globals.
     9â†’
    10â†’## Usage
    11â†’
    12â†’Consider an INI file such as the following:
    13â†’
    14â†’```ini
    15â†’; This comment is being ignored
    16â†’scope = global
    17â†’
    18â†’[database]
    19â†’user = dbuser
    20â†’password = dbpassword
    21â†’database = use_this_database
    22â†’
    23â†’[paths.default]
    24â†’datadir = /var/lib/data
    25â†’array[] = first value
    26â†’array[] = second value
    27â†’array[] = third value
    28â†’```
    29â†’
    30â†’You can **read**, **modify** and **write** it like so:
    31â†’
    32â†’```js
    33â†’import { writeFile , readFile } from 'node:fs/promises'
    34â†’import { stringify , parse } from 'ini'
    35â†’
    36â†’//  Read INI file as text
    37â†’
    38â†’let text = await readFile(`./Original.ini`,{
    39â†’    encoding : 'utf-8'
    40â†’})
    41â†’
    42â†’//  Parse text data to object
    43â†’
    44â†’const config = parse(text)
    45â†’
    46â†’//  Modify data object
    47â†’
    48â†’config.scope = 'local'
    49â†’config.database.database = 'use_another_database'
    50â†’config.paths.default.tmpdir = '/tmp'
    51â†’delete config.paths.default.datadir
    52â†’config.paths.default.array.push('fourth value')
    53â†’
    54â†’//  Stringify data object
    55â†’
    56â†’text = stringify(config,{ 
    57â†’    section : 'section' 
    58â†’})
    59â†’
    60â†’//  Write INI file as text
    61â†’
    62â†’await writeFile(`./Modified.ini`,text)
    63â†’```
    64â†’
    65â†’The written file will contain the following:
    66â†’
    67â†’```ini
    68â†’[section]
    69â†’scope=local
    70â†’[section.database]
    71â†’user=dbuser
    72â†’password=dbpassword
    73â†’database=use_another_database
    74â†’[section.paths.default]
    75â†’tmpdir=/tmp
    76â†’array[]=first value
    77â†’array[]=second value
    78â†’array[]=third value
    79â†’array[]=fourth value
    80â†’```
    81â†’
    82â†’## API
    83â†’
    84â†’### Parse
    85â†’
    86â†’Attempts to turn the given INI string into a nested data object.
    87â†’
    88â†’```js
    89â†’// You can also use `decode`
    90â†’const object = parse(`<INI Text>`) 
    91â†’```
    92â†’
    93â†’### Stringify
    94â†’
    95â†’Encodes the given data object as an INI formatted string.
    96â†’
    97â†’```js
    98â†’// You can also use `encode`
    99â†’stringify(object,{
   100â†’
   101â†’    /**
   102â†’     *  Whether to insert spaces before & after `=`
   103â†’     * 
   104â†’     *  Disabled by default to have better 
   105â†’     *  compatibility with old picky parsers.
   106â†’     */
   107â†’
   108â†’    whitespace : false ,
   109â†’
   110â†’    /**
   111â†’     *  Whether to align the `=` character for each section.
   112â†’     *  -> Also enables the `whitespace` option
   113â†’     */
   114â†’
   115â†’    align : false ,
   116â†’
   117â†’    /**
   118â†’     *  Identifier to use for global items 
   119â†’     *  and to prepend to all other sections.
   120â†’     */
   121â†’
   122â†’    section ,
   123â†’
   124â†’    /**
   125â†’     *  Whether to sort all sections & their keys alphabetically.
   126â†’     */
   127â†’
   128â†’    sort : false ,
   129â†’
   130â†’    /**
   131â†’     *  Whether to insert a newline after each section header.
   132â†’     * 
   133â†’     *  The TOSHIBA & FlashAir parser require this format. 
   134â†’     */
   135â†’
   136â†’    newline : false ,
   137â†’
   138â†’    /**
   139â†’     *  Which platforms line-endings should be used.
   140â†’     * 
   141â†’     *  win32 -> CR+LF
   142â†’     *  other -> LF
   143â†’     * 
   144â†’     *  Default is the current platform
   145â†’     */
   146â†’
   147â†’    platform ,
   148â†’
   149â†’    /**
   150â†’     *  Whether to append `[]` to array keys.
   151â†’     * 
   152â†’     *  Some parsers treat duplicate names by themselves as arrays
   153â†’     */
   154â†’
   155â†’    bracketedArray : true
   156â†’
   157â†’})
   158â†’```
   159â†’
   160â†’*For backwards compatibility any string passed as the*  
   161â†’*options parameter is treated as the `section` option.*
   162â†’
   163â†’```js
   164â†’stringify(object,'section')
   165â†’```
   166â†’
   167â†’### Un / Escape
   168â†’
   169â†’Turn the given string into a safe to  
   170â†’use key or value in your INI file.
   171â†’
   172â†’```js
   173â†’safe(`"unsafe string"`) // -> \"unsafe string\"
   174â†’```
   175â†’
   176â†’Or reverse the process with:
   177â†’
   178â†’```js
   179â†’unsafe(`\\"safe string\\"`) // -> "safe string"
   180â†’```
SECURITY.md
lib/ini.js
     3â†’const encode = (obj, opt = {}) => {
    80â†’function splitSections (str, separator) {
   106â†’const decode = (str, opt = {}) => {
   212â†’const isQuoted = val => {
   217â†’const safe = val => {
   230â†’const unsafe = val => {
